     \n                                                \n            \n        \n    \n        \n                                                                                                                                                                    \n                \n    \n    \n        \n    \n\n    \n    \n            \n    \n    \n            \n    \n    \n                                                        \n                                \n                                \n                                                \n            \n        \n    \n        \n                                                                                                                                                                    \n            \n    \n    \n        \n                    \n                        \n                                    \n\n\n\n\u003cdiv id=\"article-body\" itemprop=\"articleBody\"\u003e\u003cdiv id=\"custom_block_0\"\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eKey Takeaways\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cdiv\u003e \n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e Microsoft confirms that TPM 2.0 requirement for Windows 11 is \u0026#34;non-negotiable\u0026#34;. \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e The company emphasizes the necessity for secure and future-proof systems. \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e Consumers must upgrade hardware for official Windows 11 support. \u003c/li\u003e\n \u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eWith Windows 10 leaving support in October 2025, people are looking for ways to upgrade to Windows 11 without destroying perfectly good hardware. However, people have held hope that Microsoft would back off the operating system\u0026#39;s TPM 2.0 requirement, the biggest pain point keeping older hardware from getting official support. It was a long shot, but it was possible. Well, it turns out that Microsoft has thoroughly dashed that hope, signaling that people have to upgrade or get left behind.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv data-include-community-rating=\"false\" id=\"acec-4bcd-876dcf94a0c9\" data-nosnippet=\"\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.xda-developers.com/windows-11-24h2/\"\u003e\u003cdiv data-img-url=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg\" data-modal-id=\"single-image-modal\" data-modal-container-id=\"single-image-modal-container\" data-img-caption=\"\u0026#34;\u0026#34;\"\u003e\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 1024px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=422\u0026amp;h=268\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=422\u0026amp;h=268\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 768px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=310\u0026amp;h=220\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=310\u0026amp;h=220\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 481px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=720\u0026amp;h=400\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=720\u0026amp;h=400\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 0px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=432\u0026amp;h=260\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=432\u0026amp;h=260\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003cimg width=\"2400\" height=\"1600\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" alt=\"Text reading Windows 11 2024 Update over a blue background\" data-img-url=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg\" src=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg\"/\u003e \u003c/picture\u003e \u003c/figure\u003e \u003c/div\u003e \u003c/a\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan data-field=\"label\"\u003eRelated\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003ch5\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.xda-developers.com/windows-11-24h2/\" title=\"The Windows 11 2024 Update is now available — here\u0026#39;s what\u0026#39;s new and why it\u0026#39;s not Windows 12\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e The Windows 11 2024 Update is now available — here\u0026#39;s what\u0026#39;s new and why it\u0026#39;s not Windows 12 \u003c/a\u003e \u003c/h5\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe Windows 11 2024 Update will bring a ton of changes to the operating system, including better support for Arm devices.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/div\u003e \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"microsoft-confirms-that-the-tpm-2-0-requirement-is-quot-non-negotiable-quot\"\u003e Microsoft confirms that the TPM 2.0 requirement is \u0026#34;non-negotiable\u0026#34; \u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cdiv data-img-url=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg\" data-modal-id=\"single-image-modal\" data-modal-container-id=\"single-image-modal-container\" data-img-caption=\"\u0026#34;\u0026#34;\"\u003e\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 1024px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=825\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=825\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 768px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=825\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=825\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 481px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=800\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=800\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 0px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=500\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=500\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003cimg width=\"3000\" height=\"2000\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" alt=\"Running Windows 11 on a Yaber K3 projector\" data-img-url=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg\" src=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/10/yaber-k3-6.jpg\"/\u003e \u003c/picture\u003e \u003c/figure\u003e \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe details were revealed in a blog post on the Windows IT Pro Blog titled \u0026#34;\u003ca href=\"https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/blog/windows-itpro-blog/tpm-2-0-%E2%80%93-a-necessity-for-a-secure-and-future-proof-windows-11/4339066\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eTPM 2.0 – a necessity for a secure and future-proof Windows 11\u003c/a\u003e\u0026#34; (and with a title like that, you can probably tell where this is going). The blog post breaks down what TPM is, why Microsoft created the TPM 2.0 requirement for Windows 11, and what it does for the system.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eHowever, near the end is this bit of information, emphasis ours:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBy instituting TPM 2.0 as a \n\u003cstrong\u003enon-negotiable standard\u003c/strong\u003e\n for the future of Windows, we elevate the security benchmark. It allows you and us to better align with the growing need for formidable data protection in the modern digital sphere.\u003c/p\u003e\n \u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAs such, it\u0026#39;s clear that Microsoft will never back down from its TPM 2.0 standard; instead, it will put the onus on the consumer to upgrade their hardware. Sure enough, right after this passage is a guide on how to check the TPM of your hardware and what to do if you\u0026#39;re still on 1.0.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIf you\u0026#39;re thinking of \u003ca href=\"https://www.xda-developers.com/install-windows-11-unsupported-pc/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003einstalling Windows 11 on unsupported hardware\u003c/a\u003e, Microsoft has thought of that too. In fact, a few days before this blog post, the company \u003ca href=\"https://www.xda-developers.com/microsoft-warning-to-windows-11-incompatible-hardware/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003epublished a warning to all users using Windows 11 on older hardware\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n    \n        \n\n    \n\n        \n\n\n                \n        \n        \n\n\n        \n\n\n\n\n\n                    \n        \n    \u003c/article\u003e\n\n    \n            \n        \u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e",
